KOG0200: Tyrosine- kinase that acts as cell-surface receptor for cytokine KITLG SCF and plays an essential role in regulation of cell survival and proliferation, hematopoiesis, stem cell maintenance, gametogenesis, mast cell development, migration and function, and in melanogenesis. In response to KITLG SCF binding, KIT can activate several signaling pathways. Phosphorylates PIK3R1, PLCG1, SH2B2 APS and CBL. Activates AKT1 signaling pathway by phosphorylation of PIK3R1, regulatory subunit of phosphatidylinositol 3-kinase. Activated KIT also transmits signals via GRB2 and activation of RAS, RAF1 and MAP kinases MAPK1 ERK2 and or MAPK3 ERK1. Promotes activation of STAT members STAT1, STAT3, STAT5A and STAT5B. Activation of PLCG1 leads to production of cellular signaling molecules diacylglycerol and inositol 1,4,5-trisphosphate. KIT signaling is modulated by phosphatases, and by rapid internalization and degradation of receptor. Activated KIT promotes phosphorylation of phosphatases PTPN6 SHP-1 and PTPRU, and of transcription factors STAT1, STAT3, STAT5A and STAT5B. Promotes phosphorylation of PIK3R1, CBL, CRK (isoform Crk-II), LYN, MAPK1 ERK2 and or MAPK3 ERK1, PLCG1, SRC and SHC1 (By similarity)
